### Rule, Domain and Range of a Function

We shall introduce the formal definition of a function.

**Definition 2.3.1** (Function): A relation \(f:X\to Y\) is a function if and only if for each element \(x\in X\), there exists exactly one element \(y\in Y\) such that \(f(x)=y\).

In the above definition, the element \(x\) is mapped to the element \(y\), and \(y\) is said to be the **image** of \(x\).

A function f can be expressed algebraically as

\[f:x\mapsto f(x),\ \ \ x\in X,\]

where \(f(x)\) is the **rule** of the function f, and the set \(X\) is the **domain** ("inputs") of the function f.

The domain of function f is denoted by \(D_{t}\). Alternatively, a function f can be expressed as

\[y=f(x),\ \ x\in X\qquad\text{ or }\qquad f:X\to Y,\ x\mapsto f(x),\]

where the set \(Y\) is the **codomain** of the function f (usually it is the set of real numbers \(\mathbb{R}\)).

