### Determining the Rule of a Composite Function

**Example 5.2.1**: The functions f and g are defined as

\[\begin{split}\text{f}:&\,x\mapsto x+1,\qquad x\in \mathbb{R},\\ \text{g}:&\,x\mapsto x^{2}\,,\qquad x\in\mathbb{R}. \end{split}\]

Assuming that fg and gf exists, find \(\text{fg}(x)\) and \(\text{gf}(x)\).

_Solution:_

\[\text{fg}(x)=\text{f}\left(\text{g}(x)\right)=\text{f}\left(x^{2}\right)=x^{2} +1;\qquad\quad\text{gf}(x)=\text{g}\left(\text{f}(x)\right)=\text{g}(x+1)=(x+1) ^{2}.\]

**Remark: Examples 5.0.1** and 5.2.1 illustrate the fact that generally gf and fg are **NOT** equivalent, that is, composition of functions are not commutative.

### Determining the Range of a Composite Function

There are typically 2 methods of determining the range of a composite function, say gf.

**Method 1:** Using the graphs of both \(y=\mathrm{f}(x)\) and \(y=\mathrm{g}(x)\)

* The key idea of this method is to obtain \(\mathrm{R}_{\mathrm{f}}\) first graphically from \(y=\mathrm{f}(x)\), and then use \(\mathrm{R}_{\mathrm{f}}\) to find \(\mathrm{R}_{\mathrm{gf}}\) graphically from \(y=\mathrm{g}(x)\).
* You may wish to recall how to find the range of a function using its rule and domain (refer to Page 6) and using GC (refer to Appendixes A1 and A2).

**Method 2:** Sketching the graph of the composite function \(y=\mathrm{gf}(x)\), \(x\in D_{\mathrm{gf}}\).

* The GC may be used to sketch the composite function (Beware of the limitations of GC!)
* In certain situations, for example, there is an unknown constant in the rule of gf, algebraic methods are required.
* The range of the composite function is determined from the graph.

**Method 3:**

* The 2 methods above are **NOT** necessary to find \(\mathrm{R}_{\mathrm{gf}}\) when \(R_{\mathrm{f}}=D_{\mathrm{g}}\), because \(R_{\mathrm{gf}}=R_{\mathrm{g}}\). Similarly when \(R_{\mathrm{g}}=D_{\mathrm{f}}\), \(R_{\mathrm{fg}}=R_{\mathrm{f}}\).

